The Telegraph - Calcutta : Bengal

 BRIEFS

 Calcutta, March 1: The cabinet today approved the proposal to shift the South 24-Parganas district headquarters from Alipore to Barui- pur, 20 km from the city.

 Dipankar Mukher- jee, the chief ministers secretary, said the cabinet okayed the personnel and administrative reforms departments proposal unanimously. Around 2,600 acres will be requisitioned for construction of the administrative blocks in three phases. The cabinet also greenlighted the creation of 550 teacher posts for non-government and 150 for government colleges.

 Barasat: The body of six-year-old Ujjal Roy was found under a tree at Ashoknagar in Habra, North 24-Parganas, on Tuesday. He was last seen playing near his school, a kilometre from where the body was found and 35 km from Calcutta. Some of his classmates are being questioned.

 Calcutta: Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee will leave the city on Thursday for a three-day visit to Vietnam. Accompanied by a business delegation, the chief minister will go to an industrial park and have an interactive se- ssion with the Vietnam Chamber of Commerce. 

 Calcutta: Border Security Force personnel have seized smuggled goods worth about Rs 9.87 crore along the Bangladesh border in south Bengal this year. A BSF spokesman said 1,007 Bangladeshis and 436 Indians have been held for crossing over without valid papers.

 Durgapur: Police have rescued Santoshi Devi, 30, who had lopped off a portion of her tongue and was about to sacrifice the whole of it to please Lord Shiv. The housewife had been told that would better her relationship with her husband.




